text:
The recently released Brian 2 simulator[1] is a fundamental rewrite of the popular Brian simulator[2, 3] for spiking neural networks. The strength of the simulator is that it combines ease of use and flexibility with high simulation performance. Ease of use and flexibility is achieved by a system that allows the user to describe neuronal and synaptic models as well as initial conditions and synaptic connectivity with mathematical notation and a system of explicit physical units[4]. The high simulation performance is achieved by using a code generation approach[5] that transparently generates efficient code in a compiled language like C++ from the user-provided model descriptions. From the user's perspective, Brian 2 is used as a library for the Python programming language, the code generation happens without any user intervention "behind the scenes".

This poster gives a general overview over Brian's features and technology and presents several recent noteworthy improvements, in particular:
* A new syntax for efficient synapse generation, based on Python's generator syntax;
* A system to "snapshot" the simulation state either to memory or to disk and to "roll back" to such a state later;
* An improved system for specifying and loading neuronal morphologies for multicompartmental simulations that are solved efficiently with optional support of parallel execution on multiple processor cores.

Brian 2 is made available under a free software license and all development takes place in public code repositories[1]. Documentation, tutorials and examples can be found online[6].
